# Technology Stack & Dependency Versions

This document outlines the complete technology stack, dependency versions, and version-specific best practices for the content-hub-next project.

## Core Framework & Runtime

### Next.js 16.1.4

**Version Notes:**
- Latest stable version (as of project setup)
- Full App Router support (Pages Router deprecated for new features)
- Built-in React Server Components support
- Turbopack as default bundler (faster than Webpack)

**Best Practices:**
- âś… **Always use App Router** - Never use Pages Router (`/pages`) for new features
- âś… **Server Components by default** - Only add `"use client"` when needed for interactivity
- âś… **Use async Server Components** - Leverage async/await in Server Components for data fetching
- âś… **Metadata API** - Use `metadata` export for SEO instead of `<Head>`
- âś… **Route Handlers** - Use `route.ts` files in `app/api/` for API endpoints
- âś… **Streaming & Suspense** - Use `loading.tsx` and Suspense boundaries for better UX
- âś… **Server Actions** - Prefer Server Actions over API routes for mutations

**File Conventions:**
- `page.tsx` - Route pages
- `layout.tsx` - Shared layouts
- `loading.tsx` - Loading states
- `error.tsx` - Error boundaries
- `not-found.tsx` - 404 pages
- `route.ts` - API route handlers
- `template.tsx` - Re-rendering templates

**Example:**
```typescript
// âś… Good - Server Component (default)
export default async function Page() {
  const data = await fetchData();
  return <div>{data}</div>;
}

// âś… Good - Client Component (when needed)
"use client";
export default function InteractiveComponent() {
  const [state, setState] = useState();
  return <button onClick={() => setState(...)}>Click</button>;
}
```

### React 19.2.3

**Version Notes:**
- Latest React 19 major version
- React Compiler support (automatic memoization)
- New hooks: `useFormStatus`, `useFormState`, `useActionState`
- Improved Server Components support
- Better hydration error messages

**Best Practices:**
- âś… **React Compiler** - Leverage automatic optimizations (no manual `useMemo`/`useCallback` needed)
- âś… **Server Actions** - Use with `useFormStatus` for form handling
- âś… **Async Components** - Fully supported in React 19
- âś… **Ref as Prop** - Use `ref` as a regular prop (no `forwardRef` needed)
- âś… **Context as Provider** - Simplified context usage

**Breaking Changes to Watch:**
- `ref` is now a regular prop (no `forwardRef` wrapper needed)
- Some deprecated APIs removed
- Stricter hydration checks

**Example:**
```typescript
// âś… Good - React 19 Server Action with form status
"use client";
import { useFormStatus } from "react-dom";

function SubmitButton() {
  const { pending } = useFormStatus();
  return <button disabled={pending}>Submit</button>;
}
```

### React DOM 19.2.3

**Version Notes:**
- Matches React 19 version
- Improved hydration
- Better error boundaries

**Best Practices:**
- âś… Keep React and React DOM versions in sync
- âś… Use error boundaries for better error handling

## Language & Type Safety

### TypeScript 5.x

**Version Notes:**
- Latest TypeScript major version
- Improved type inference
- Better performance
- Enhanced decorator support

**Best Practices:**
- âś… **Strict Mode Enabled** - Already configured in `tsconfig.json`
- âś… **Type Everything** - Use interfaces/types for all props and data structures
- âś… **Avoid `any`** - Use `unknown` or proper types instead
- âś… **Type Imports** - Use `import type` for type-only imports
- âś… **Path Aliases** - Use `@/*` aliases (configured in `tsconfig.json`)

**Configuration:**
- Target: ES2017
- Module: ESNext
- Module Resolution: bundler (optimized for Next.js)
- JSX: react-jsx

**Example:**
```typescript
// âś… Good - Proper typing
interface UserProps {
  name: string;
  age: number;
}

export function User({ name, age }: UserProps) {
  return <div>{name} ({age})</div>;
}

// âś… Good - Type imports
import type { NextRequest } from "next/server";
```

## Styling & UI

### Tailwind CSS 4.x

**Version Notes:**
- Major version update with new features
- Improved performance
- Better CSS variable support
- New utility classes

**Best Practices:**
- âś… **CSS Variables** - Use CSS variables for theming (configured in `components.json`)
- âś… **PostCSS Integration** - Uses `@tailwindcss/postcss` plugin
- âś… **Utility Classes** - Prefer utility classes over custom CSS
- âś… **Component Variants** - Use `class-variance-authority` for component variants
- âś… **Responsive Design** - Use Tailwind breakpoints (`sm:`, `md:`, `lg:`, etc.)

**Configuration:**
- Base color: neutral
- CSS variables: enabled
- Style: new-york (shadcn/ui)

**Example:**
```typescript
// âś… Good - Tailwind utilities with CVA
import { cva } from "class-variance-authority";

const buttonVariants = cva(
  "inline-flex items-center justify-center rounded-md",
  {
    variants: {
      variant: {
        default: "bg-primary text-primary-foreground",
        destructive: "bg-destructive text-destructive-foreground",
      },
    },
  }
);
```

### shadcn/ui (via components.json)

**Version Notes:**
